aws::graph::propositions: # Aviation Accident Analysis of Corben Baby Ace D in Lincoln, California
The accident occurred in Lincoln, California.
The accident occurred on October 5, 2014, at 12:15 Local time.
The aircraft involved was a Corben Baby Ace D.
The aircraft registration was N3RH.
The defining event of the accident was nose over/nose down.
The flight was conducted under Part 91: General aviation - Personal.
The accident number was WPR15LA003.
The aircraft sustained substantial damage.
There were no injuries to the sole occupant.
The pilot performed an uneventful takeoff.
The pilot performed a straight-out departure.
The pilot leveled the airplane about 1,000 ft above ground level.
The engine began to sputter at 1,000 ft above ground level.
The engine subsequently lost power.
The pilot initiated a return to the departure airport.
The pilot initiated a forced landing to a nearby field due to the low altitude.
During the landing, the main landing gear collapsed.
The airplane nosed over during the landing.
Postaccident examination revealed the gascolator screen was partially restricted with red, sandlike debris.
Postaccident examination revealed the fuel outlet port was partially restricted with red, sandlike debris.
The debris restricted the fuel flow to the carburetor.
The restricted fuel flow led to the loss of engine power.
The National Transportation Safety Board determined the probable cause of the accident to be total loss of engine power due to fuel starvation.
The fuel starvation resulted from debris restricting the fuel flow within the fuel system.
The aircraft's fuel filter-strainer capability was exceeded.
The aircraft's fuel fluid level was a finding in the investigation.

text:
# Aviation Investigation Final Report

## Location:
Lincoln, California

## Date & Time: 
October 5, 2014, 12:15 Local

## Aircraft:
CORBEN BABY ACE D

## Defining Event:
Nose over/nose down

## Flight Conducted Under:
Part 91: General aviation - Personal

## Accident Number:
WPR15LA003

## Registration:
N3RH

## Aircraft Damage:
Substantial

## Injuries:
1 None

## Analysis

Following an uneventful takeoff and straight-out departure, the pilot leveled the airplane about 1,000 ft above ground level, at which point, the engine began to sputter, and it subsequently lost power. The pilot initiated a return to the departure airport; however, due to the low altitude, he initiated a forced landing to a nearby field. During the landing, the main landing gear collapsed, and the airplane nosed over. Postaccident examination of the airplane revealed that the gascolator screen and fuel outlet port were partially restricted with red, sandlike debris, which would have restricted the fuel flow to the carburetor and led to the loss of engine power.

## Probable Cause and Findings

The National Transportation Safety Board determines the probable cause(s) of this accident to be:

The total loss of engine power due to fuel starvation, which resulted from debris restricting the fuel flow within the fuel system.

## Findings

|-|-|
| Aircraft | Fuel filter-strainer - Capability exceeded |
| Aircraft | Fuel - Fluid level |
